x = (n(n+1)) / (n+2)

For x to be a natural number, n+2 must divide n(n+1).
n(n+1) = n² + n
n+2 divides n² + n
n+2 divides (n² + n) - (n-2)(n+2)
(n-2)(n+2) = n² - 4
So (n² + n) - (n² - 4) = n + 4
So n+2 divides n+4
n+2 divides (n+4) - (n+2)
n+2 divides 2

So n+2 must be a divisor of 2. The divisors of 2 are 1, 2.
n+2=1 → n=-1 (not a natural number)
n+2=2 → n=0 (but n ≥ 2)

So this approach doesn't work for n ≥ 2.

